  "prompt": "What is the best time of the year to visit Glacier National Park?",
  "response": "The best time to visit Glacier National Park is generally considered to be **July and August**. Here's why:\n\n*   **Complete Access:** This is when the entire park is usually open, including Going-to-the-Sun Road, which is the park's most iconic and scenic drive. Opening of the full road depends on snow removal and can be delayed.\n*   **Weather:** The weather is typically warm and sunny, perfect for hiking, camping, and other outdoor activities.\n*   **Full Services:** All visitor centers, lodges, campgrounds, and other services are usually fully operational during these months.\n\nHowever, there are trade-offs:\n\n*   **Crowds:** This is the peak season, so expect large crowds at popular attractions and difficulty finding parking.\n*   **Higher Prices:** Lodging and other services are typically more expensive during July and August.\n\n**Shoulder Seasons (June & September):**\n\n*   **Fewer Crowds:** You'll encounter fewer crowds than in July and August.\n*   **Pleasant Weather:** The weather can be pleasant, although more unpredictable. Expect possible rain, and cooler temperatures, especially at night.\n*   **Partial Access:** Some areas of the park, particularly higher elevation trails and the Going-to-the-Sun Road, may still be closed or have limited access in early June due to snow. Some services may also have limited hours or not be open at all in September. Be sure to check current conditions.\n\n**Spring (May) & Fall (October):**\n\n*   **Very Few Crowds:** This is the least crowded time to visit.\n*   **Unpredictable Weather:** The weather is highly unpredictable, with chances of snow, rain, and cold temperatures.\n*   **Limited Access:** Many roads, trails, and services are closed due to snow and seasonal closures.\n\n**Winter (November - April):**\n\n*   **Very Limited Access:** Most of the park is inaccessible by car. Only certain areas near the park's entrances are open for winter activities like cross-country skiing and snowshoeing.\n*   **Extreme Weather:** Expect very cold temperatures and heavy snow.\n\n**In summary:**\n\n*   **July & August:** Best overall experience (access, weather), but most crowded and expensive.\n*   **June & September:** A good compromise between access and crowds, but weather is more unpredictable.\n*   **May & October:** Very few crowds, but limited access and unpredictable weather.\n*   **November - April:** Only for specialized winter activities.\n\n**Before you go:**\n\n*   Always check the official Glacier National Park website for current conditions, road closures, and alerts.\n*   Make reservations for lodging, camping, and activities well in advance, especially if visiting during peak season.\n*   Be prepared for variable weather conditions, no matter when you visit. Pack layers of clothing, rain gear, and sturdy hiking shoes.\n",
